The '''Russo–Susskind–Thorlacius model'''<ref> {{cite journal | last1 = Russo | first1 = Jorge | authorlink1 = Jorge Russo | last2 = Susskind | first2 = Leonard | authorlink2 = Leonard Susskind | last3 = Thorlacius | first3 = L&aacute;rus | authorlink3 = L&aacute;rus Throlacius | date = 15 Oct 1992 | title = The Endpoint of Hawking Evaporation | journal = Physical Review | volume = 46 | issue = 8 | series = D | pages = 3444–3449 | doi = 10.1103/PhysRevD.46.3444 | pmid = 10015289 | arxiv = hep-th/9206070 | bibcode = 1992PhRvD..46.3444R }} </ref> or '''RST model''' in short is a modification of the [[CGHS model]] to take care of [[conformal anomaly|conformal anomalies]]. In the CGHS model, if we include [[Faddeev-Popov ghost]]s to gauge-fix diffeomorphisms in the [[conformal gauge]], they contribute an anomaly of -24. Each matter field contributes an anomaly of 1. So, unless N=24, we will have [[gravitational anomaly|gravitational anomalies]]. To the CGHS action :<math>S_{\text{CGHS}} = \frac{1}{2\pi} \int d^2x\, \sqrt{-g}\left\{ e^{-2\phi} \left[ R + 4\left( \nabla\phi \right)^2 + 4\lambda^2 \right] - \sum^N_{i=1} \frac{1}{2}\left( \nabla f_i \right)^2 \right\}</math>, the following term :<math>S_{\text{RST}} = - \frac{\kappa}{8\pi} \int d^2x\, \sqrt{-g} \left[ R\frac{1}{\nabla^2}R - 2\phi R \right]</math> is added, where ''&kappa;'' is either <math>(N-24)/12</math> or <math>N/12</math> depending upon whether ghosts are considered. The nonlocal term leads to [[Action at a distance|nonlocality]]. In the conformal gauge, :<math>S_{\text{RST}} = -\frac{\kappa}{\pi} \int dx^+\,dx^- \left[ \partial_+ \rho \partial_- \rho + \phi \partial_+ \partial_- \rho \right]</math>.
It might appear as if the theory is local in the conformal gauge, but this overlooks the fact that the Raychaudhuri equations are still nonlocal.
