A '''ranked society''' in [[anthropology]] is one that [[ranking|ranks]] individuals in terms of their [[genealogical]] distance from the [[Tribal chief|chief]]. Closer relatives of the chief have higher rank or social status than more distant ones. When individuals and groups rank about equally, competition for positions of leadership may occur. In some cases rank is assigned to entire villages rather than individuals or families. The idea of a ranked society was criticized by [[Max Weber]] and [[Karl Marx]]. Ranks in ranked society are the different levels, platforms, or classes that determine someone’s influence on political aspects, votes, decision making, etc. A person’s ranking also gives them societal power ( power within their civilisation ). 

